PART 1: CRITICAL SPSS IMPORT QUIRKS (Naming & Matching)
The Exact Match Rule: You must use the exact list of imported variable names I provide at the bottom of this prompt for your commands. Do not guess how SPSS truncated the names.

The "Squish" Rule: When referencing the messy imported variable names, ensure they match the squished, space-free format of the provided variable list (e.g., "What is your age?" becomes Whatisyourage).

The 64-Character Limit: SPSS strictly limits variable names to 64 characters. The provided variable list reflects this truncation.

The Alphabetical Suffix Rule & "TO" Method: For matrix/repeated questions that share the same introductory text, SPSS forces uniqueness by appending an underscore and an alphabetical suffix (_A, _B, etc.). When recoding these, use the TO keyword. Capture the full string of the first question, use TO, and end with the exact truncated string of the last question featuring its suffix (e.g., RECODE Herearesomedifferentway...r TO Herearesomedifferentway..._S).

PART 2: DATA TRANSFORMATION & FORMATTING RULES
The RECODE INTO Transformation: Write a RECODE block that converts the text answers into logical numeric codes and outputs them into clean, short, professional variable names (max 64 chars, NO spaces, e.g., Age_Group, ATTC_1). Group variables sharing the exact same scale together to save lines.

Handling Open-Ended Strings: If the questionnaire has open-ended text or metadata (Names, IDs, Emails), DO NOT RECODE THEM. Use RENAME VARIABLES to give them a clean name.

Variable & Value Labels: Apply VARIABLE LABELS using the exact question text (escape single quotes by doubling them: ' becomes ''). Apply VALUE LABELS based on the questionnaire choices.

Missing Values & Logic (88/99): Assign 88 'NA (Not Applicable)' and 99 'NS (Not Specified)' ONLY to questions impacted by exclusion criteria or conditional skip logic. Generate the explicit MISSING VALUES varname (88, 99) command only for these affected variables.

Widths & Decimals (FORMATS): Explicitly define widths using FORMATS varname (Fw.d).

Use F2.0 (Width 2, Decimals 0) for variables containing 88 or 99 missing logic, or double-digit scales (e.g., 10-15).

Use F1.0 (Width 1, Decimals 0) for standard single-digit scales (e.g., 1-5 scales).

Measurement Levels: Set VARIABLE LEVEL (NOMINAL, ORDINAL, or SCALE).

Column Display Width: Use the VARIABLE WIDTH command to set all recoded and renamed variables to (8) so the SPSS Data View grid is clean and readable.

Cleanup: End the script with EXECUTE.

